title: Will Barnaby Joyce win the upcoming by-election in New England, Australia?
preds: New England by-election: 'Landslide' win expected for Joyce as polls open https://www.sbs.com.au/news/article/2017/12/02/new-england-election-landslide-win-expected-joyce-polls-open
He seems pretty favourite to win by all accounts but he is facing 16 candidates.
Won in the past, still popular so likely to win.

Oooo!  An Australian question! Barnaby won 52% of the primary vote against Tony Windsor (a _very_ high profile, experienced, and popular candidate) just over 12 months ago, and won with 17% margin of the 2-party-preferred vote (which in Australian terms is about as one-sided as a result gets).  Tony Windsor is not running again. New England has been held by the Country/National Party (or Tony Windsor, who used to be a member of the Nationals) since 1919.  It is almost inconceivable that any of the other candidates this time will come close: none of them (if independent) or their parties broke 8% in the previous election.  "Informal vote" ran 3rd behind Barnaby and Tony in a field of 10 candidates. Barnaby to win without even needing to go to preferences, probably with over 60% of the primary vote.
When this election has upcome (and presumably downgone), Joyce will have won.
